  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just an academic concept—it's a lived reality for many people I've encountered in my work and life. As a retired retail worker from Bologna, I've seen how even simple interactions can trigger anxiety in those who feel they don't belong in technical fields. My own experience with depression has made me sensitive to the emotional weight of being judged by others' expectations. For instance, when I tried to explain basic coding to my kids, their confusion made me feel like I was failing them, even though I was just trying to be helpful. Stereotype threat occurs when people's self-esteem is threatened by negative stereotypes about their group, like assuming women or people from lower socioeconomic backgrounds aren't good at math or science. In my case, growing up with a parent who only went to primary school while the other had a master's degree taught me early that intelligence isn't fixed—it's something you build through effort. But the pressure to conform to stereotypes can still be overwhelming. I believe we should address stereotype threat in STEM by creating environments where everyone feels safe to ask questions without fear of judgment. This means teachers and mentors needing to be aware of their language and actions, and schools should offer more hands-on, collaborative projects that don't rely on traditional testing methods. It's not about changing the system overnight but starting small—like encouraging kids to explore science through games or travel adventures, which aligns with my own hobbies. Ultimately, addressing stereotype threat requires empathy and patience, especially for those of us who've struggled with self-doubt.",
